_attributes.description: This is the regular <a> element. Use it to link to other pages or websites.
This is the HTML5 <article> element. Use it to wrap articles or other content items to give semantic meaning to your design.
This is the HTML5 <aside> element. Use it when building sidebars or when presenting related content.
This is the HTML <blockquote> element, extended with Bootstrap markup for showing attribution.

Blockquote._html:
Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Integer posuere erat a ante.

Someone famous

_attributes.description: This is the standard <strong> element. You can optionally switch it to use a <b> tag instead.

This is the multi-functional Bootstrap Button component. You have a choice of possible themes, button types and sizes. Search for the related Dropdown and Split Button components if you need your button to trigger dropdown menus.
This is the standard <p> HTML element. Use it for writing body text. It is enhanced by Bootstrap's rich styling classes, available in the Options panel.
This is the standard <div> HTML element.
This is the standard <label> HTML element for displaying labels in forms. For better accessibility, make sure that the "for" attribute points to the id of the related field.
This is the standard <fieldset> HTML element. Use it to group form fields together.
This is the <figcaption> HTML5 element. Use it inside <figure> to give images a caption.
This is the <figure> HTML5 element. Use it when embedding illustrations into articles. It groups images and <figcaption> elements together.
This is the <footer> HTML5 element. Use it as the main element of your footers to give them semantic meaning.
This is Bootstrap's form component. It is like the regular HTML <form>, but extended with styling and layout classes. Usually forms in Bootstrap contain only Form Group children.
This is the <header> HTML5 element. It represents a group of introductory or navigational aids. It may contain some heading elements but also other elements like a logo, a search form and so on.
This is the HTML heading component. You can choose which HTML tag is used - from <h1> to <h6>.
This is the <hgroup> HTML5 element. It is used to group together heading elements.
This is the <hr> HTML element. It is displayed as a horizontal rule. If you wish to combine it with a heading, look for the Page Header component.
This is Bootstrap's icon component. You can choose from a number of available icon fonts. You can modify the icon's size and color by changing its CSS font-size and color properties.
This is the <image> HTML element. You can control its size, source, style and responsiveness from the Options panel.
This is the <input type="checkbox" /> HTML element. If you wish to use it in Bootstrap forms, look for the Checkbox With Label component.
This is the <input type="color" /> HTML5 element. In modern browsers it displays a color picker for selecting color values.
This component combines a number of date and time related HTML5 input elements into one. Choose the type you need from the Options panel.
This is the <input type="email" /> HTML5 element. Use it in forms to ask users for their email addresses.
This is the <input type="file" /> HTML element. Use it to add file upload functionality to your forms. Remember to set the form's Encoding to Multipart.
This is the <input type="hidden" /> HTML element. Use it to pass data to your form handling backend script.
This is the <input type="number" /> HTML5 element. Use it to when you wish to limit the entered text only to numbers.
This is the <input type="password" /> HTML element. Use it when you need to collect passwords and other sensitive data.

This is the <input type="radio" /> HTML element. Place several components of this type with the same "name" attribute but different values to get a radio group. If you wish to show a label next to it, look for the Radio With Label component.
This is the <input type="range" /> HTML5 element. In modern browsers it is visualized as a slider with minimum and maximum values.
This is the <input type="search" /> HTML5 element. It may be displayed differently depending on the browser and OS used.
This is the <input type="tel" /> HTML5 element. It is used for entering phone numbers. Mobile devices show specialized keyboard that makes text entry easier.
This is the standard <input type="text" /> HTML element. Use it to collect textual data from users without a specific format.
This is the standard <textarea> HTML element. Use it to collect multi-line textual data.
This is the <input type="url" /> HTML5 element. It is used for entering and validating URL addresses.
This is the standard <em> element. You can optionally switch it to use a <i> tag instead.
This is the standard <legend> HTML element. It is used as a caption for the content of fieldsets.
This is the standard HTML list element. From the options, you can switch it to use either <ol> or <ul> elements.
This is the standard <p> HTML element. Use it for writing body text. It is enhanced by Bootstrap's rich styling classes, available in the Options panel.
This is a Bootstrap component for embedding external content. It maintains its aspect ratio regardless of screen size, which makes it a good fit for responsive video embedding.
This is the <section> HTML5 element. It represents a generic section of content inside your document.
This is the <select> HTML element. It is a standard control, visualized as a dropdown list in browsers. You can control the items and groups from the Options panel.

Select._html:
<select>
            <optgroup label="This is a group">
                <option value="12" selected="">This is item 1</option>
                <option value="13">This is item 2</option>
                <option value="14">This is item 3</option>
            </optgroup>
        </select>

_attributes.description: This is the <small> HTML element. It is generally used to represent side-comments and small print. It is displayed with a smaller font-size and lighter color than main content.
This is the standard <span> HTML element.
This is the standard <table> HTML element. It is enhanced with Bootstrap styling classes, available from the Options panel.
This is the standard <td> HTML element. Drop it inside table rows to create columns.
This is the standard <tr> HTML element. Drop it inside tables to create rows.
